\par 
\par Commander Sparrow trotted down the ramp from the tube landing, slowed as he stepped into the cavernous, floodlighted gloom of the underground submarine moorage.  A fine mist of conden
sation from the rock ceiling far away in upper blackness beat against his face.  He picked his way through the pattern of scurrying jitneys, darting, intent people.  
Ahead of him, the bulbous whale mound of his subtug rose above the pier; a 140-foot Wagnerian diva center stage beneath banks of floodlights.
\par 
\par Instructions from the final Security session jangled through his mind.
\par 
\par "Your crew has the top Security rating of the service, but you must remain alert for sleepers."
\par 
\par "In my crew?  Hell, man, I've known them all for years.  Bonnett's been with me eight years.  Joe Garcia and I served together before the war.  Heppner and --"  His face had crimsoned.  "What about the new E-officer?"
\par 
\par "You won't need to worry about him.  Now, the inspectors assure us there are no enemy signal devices aboard your boat."
\par 
\par "Then why this gadget in my neck?"
\par 
\par "That's just an added precaution."
\par 
\par "What about this new man?  What's his E-rating?"
\par 
\par "He's one of the best in the service.  Here, look at his record."
\par 
\par "Limited combat experience in gulf patrol!  He's practically a dryback!"
\par 
\par "But look at his E-rating."
\par 
\par "Limited combat!"
\par 
\par A jitney driver shouted at Sparrow, bringing him out of his reverie.  He glanced at his wrist watch:  0738 -- twenty-two minutes until castoff.  His stomach tightened.  He quickened his steps.
\par 
\par Damn Security's last-minute details!
\par 
\par Across the ebony velvet of the mooring pool he could see the glow tubes outlining the marine tunnel.  Down the 160-mile slant of that tunnel, out into the underwater deeps of De Soto Canyon and the Gulf of Mexico -- and beyond -- ranged the enemy.  
An enemy grown suddenly, terrifyingly, one hundred percent effective against vessels such as his.
\par 
