\par 
\par Sparrow frowned, shrugged.  He thumbed his chest mike:  "Joe, Les -- hear this.  This tube may be booby-trapped.  If anything happens to Johnny and me, you two drop the tow and head for home.  That's an order."
\par 
\par Johnny! thought Ramsey.  He called me Johnny!  And then he remembered:  We've met the enemy.  The old magic is dead.  Enter the new magic.
\par 
\par "We'll want a record of this," said Sparrow.  He took a camera from a drawer, racked it above the bench, focused it.  "Okay," he said.  "You're the expert on these gadgets."
\par 
\par Ramsey spoke without looking up from the tube:  "A half hour of just looking at this thing, studying all the angles, could mean the difference between success and failure."
\par 
\par "What're we looking for?"
\par 
\par "I don't really know.  Something different.  Something that hits a sour note."
\par 
\par Sparrow bent over the bench, grabbed a handhold as the Ram's deck slanted to the upflow of an undersea current.  Ramsey steadied the tube with one hand, brought up folds of the felt padding to keep the tube from rolling.  The amber light of the temperat
ure-gadget indicator on the board ahead of them flashed off, on, off.
\par 
\par Ramsey switched on the thermo repeater above the light:  thirty-four degrees.
\par 
\par Sparrow nodded at the repeater.  "The Arctic bottom drift.  It's full of food.  There'll be a sonic curtain of sea life above us."  He smiled.  "We can breathe a bit easier."
\par 
\par Ramsey shook his head.  "Not with that thing to solve."  He stared at the tube on the bench.  "If you were going to trigger that to explode, how would you do it?"
\par 
\par "A tiny wire maybe.  Break it and --"
\par 
\par "Maybe," said Ramsey.  "A better way would be to set a trigger keyed to pressure change -- if the vacuum breaks . . ."  He straightened.  "First some infra and X pictures.  Then we'll rig a vacuum jar with remote controls, handle the tube in the vacuum.  
After that we'll break the seal."
\par 
