\par An abrupt correlation interlocked in Ramsey's mind.  He glanced one more time over his search board, turned away, forced himself to walk calmly across to Bonnett.  He bent over the first officer, checked Bonnett's vampire gauge.  
CO2 diffusion .228.  Above normal by .016.  He dropped Bonnett's wrist, stood up and made a minute micro-meter-gauge reduction in anhydrase generation.
\par 
\par "What's wrong with Les?"  Sparrow stood in the aft door, gaze sweeping over the control deck.  He stepped through the door as Ramsey turned.
\par 
\par "Take it slow," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par "Wha --"  Sparrow hesitated in mid-stride.
\par 
\par Ramsey bent over Bonnett, again checked his vampire gauge, compared it with the one on his own wrist.  No change.  Too soon.  He said, "I've just formed the Ramsey Theory on why some chimpanzees died and some didn't."
\par 
\par Sparrow again moved forward, bent over Bonnett.  "What chimpanzees?"
\par 
\par "The chimps Med. I put under 400 pounds with peak anhydrase.  My advice is for you not to overexert, get excited, nervous, or --"
\par 
\par "I know about the chimps," said Sparrow.  "Do you think --"  He hesitated.
\par 
\par "Some kind of glandular upset," said Ramsey.  "What's more likely than an emotional trigger, maybe coupled to physical activity?"
\par 
\par Sparrow nodded.
\par 
\par Ramsey noted the vampire-gauge needles sinking toward normal.  He began massaging Bonnett's left arm.  "You're okay, Les.  Just relax and take it easy.  The crisis is over.  Take it easy . . . take it easy . . . take it easy . . ."
\par 
\par Bonnett's head rocked groggily.
\par 
\par "We have to avoid excitement," said Ramsey.  "Our bodies are walking a tight wire down here.  An uneasy balance."
\par 
\par Sparrow stood up, went to the search board.  "I gave Joe a sedative.  He was crying, raving.  Maybe I --"  He fell silent.
\par 
\par Bonnett opened his eyes.
\par 
\par "Remain calm," said Ramsey.  "Do you hear me, Les?"
\par 
\par The first officer nodded.
\par 
\par "There's no danger if you relax.
\par 
\par "You can't force a man to relax," said Sparrow.
\par 
\par Ramsey reached around Bonnett's head, found the nerve line on the back of his neck, massaged it.  "You're feeling better already."
\par 
\par Bonnett wet his lips with his tongue.  "'M okay.  Get back to your board."
\par 
\par "Breathe slow and easy," said Ramsey.  He stood up.
\par 
\par Bonnett swallowed, spoke as though past a thickened tongue.  "It was like quicksand.  Feelin' better now."
\par 
\par Ramsey turned toward Sparrow.  "He'll be okay now."
\par 
\par Sparrow glanced down at Bonnett.  "Stay where you are Les, until you feel like getting up."  He turned to Ramsey.  "I've been on the eyes.  The current has pulled our tow to a forty-five-degree angle across our stern.  
If we slack off the top towline we'll right but that might free the tow for a further shift."
\par 
\par "Best leave well enough alone," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par "How near the edge of this seamount are we?  The eyes don't show it."
\par 
\par "Maybe seventy-five yards.  For the tow, that is.  We were angling away from the edge when we sat down."
\par 
\par Sparrow looked at the ranging computers.  "Intermittent signal near extreme range."
\par 
\par "That cold layer is waving over us like a fan," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par Sparrow backed away from the board, looked around him, brought his attention back to Ramsey.  There was something in the way he looked at Ramsey of the same attention he gave to his boat's instruments.  
"What's this 'Long John' business?  Joe doesn't make sense."
\par 
\par Ramsey repeated what he had told Bonnett.  "Did the Ram benefit from this acquisition propensity of yours?"
\par 
\par "Not this trip, Skipper."
\par 
\par Sparrow glanced upward to the row of reactor-room telltales.  "Maybe next trip."
\par 
\par Bonnett spoke from his position on the deck.  "We're gonna have a next trip, too.  If we don't crack up like poor Hepp."
\par 
\par "We won't," said Sparrow.
\par 
\par Bonnett heaved himself to his feet.  "I'm glad we have God's word on that."
\par 
\par Sparrow gave him a searching stare, said, "I'm reassuming command, Les.  The circumstances warrant it.  I'm in no immediate danger from that radiation overage."
\par 
\par "Of course, Skipper."  There seemed a sigh of relief in Bonnett's voice.
\par 
\par Sparrow said, "I'm going back now and have another look at Joe.  I'm leaving Johnny on the search board.  All clear?"
\par 
\par "All clear, Skipper."
\par 
\par Sparrow turned his angular form slowly, went out the aft door.
\par 
\par "He's an automaton," said Ramsey, addressing the empty air where Sparrow had stood.
\par 
\par "He's under more pressure than the submarine," said Bonnett.  He took a deep breath.  "Let's you pay attention to that board."
\par 
\par Ramsey frowned, returned his attention to his gauges and dials.
\par 
\par Silence hung between them.
\par 
\par Presently, Bonnett said, "Thanks, Johnny.  Maybe you saved my life."
\par 
\par Ramsey shrugged, remained silent.
\par 
\par "I heard what you told the skipper.  It feels right.  Come to think of it, maybe you saved all of our lives."
\par 
\par "Be damned lonesome down here all alone," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par "You'd probably prefer three well-stacked blondes," said Bonnett.  "Come to think of it, that'd get my vote, too."
\par 
\par "Another signal at outer range," said Ramsey, "Six subs in net-search spacing.  They'll pass out of range in the south-east quadrant."
\par 
\par "They just ain't looking where nobody could possibly be," said Bonnett.  "Can't say that I blame them.  I still don't believe I'm here."  He glanced up at the static pressure gauge, looked quickly away.
\par 
\par "No need for two of us here," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par "Nothing except the skipper's double-team orders."
\par 
\par "Stupid orders," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par "Take it easy, lad," said Bonnett "You can't fight the Navy chain of command and you can't fight God."  He shrugged.  "And when the two are on the same team --"
\par 
\par "What makes you believe that nonsense?" asked Ramsey.
\par 
\par Bonnett froze.  "I make jokes, boy.  That's one thing.  What you just said is another thing."  He shook his head.  "I've been forty missions with the Savvy Sparrow guy.  Don't talk to me about nonsense.  I know what I've seen."
\par 
\par And you know what you want to believe, thought Ramsey.
\par 
\par Somewhere a faint dripping caught his attention:  condensation on the pipes.  The Ram suddenly assumed a cold empty feeling around him.  We're not going to make it, he thought.  A thousand alert enemy subs ranging across our track.  
It was crazy to send us out.  A desperation move.
\par 
\par The lights of his thermocouple monitor winked blindly on the instrument board.
\par 
\par God's cold cloak waving over us!  Maybe that's the best thing to believe.  Knowledge is the course of our lives.  We eat the apple and we learn just enough to make us afraid.
\par 
\par The Ram shuddered briefly as the current tugged at her tow.  The deck tilted back toward level.
\par 
\par "If we raise a big mud patch on the surface -- stirring up the bottom like a mud pie -- they'll spot it," said Bonnett.  "They'll have a sky full of buzzards this close to their own shores."
\par 
\par "How'll they see it in the fog?" asked Ramsey.  He felt a sudden lightening of his spirits.
\par 
\par "Fog topside?  How can you tell?"
\par 
\par "Skipper arranged it with God," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par "You think you're joking," said Bonnett.  He looked at Ramsey.  "You do, don't you?"
\par 
\par Ramsey reset the ranging computer in front of him.  "A man has to live with his boat -- be a part of it," he said, speaking lightly.  He felt the sudden undertow pull of thought below the words.  
It was like stepping outside his body and watching it function.  "This boat believes in God," he said.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par ***
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par The counter hands of the timelog swept around . . . around . . . around . . .  The watches changed as the Ram snuggled into the mud of the seamount.
\par 
\par Eleven days, thirty-two minutes from point of departure.
\par 
\par Sparrow stood at the control board with Ramsey, sharing the last half of the electronics officer's watch.  The sense of excess pressure outside their hull had become a thing accepted.
\par 
\par "How long since you've heard one of their packs?" asked Sparrow.
\par 
\par "Over six hours."
\par 
\par "How's the tow?"
\par 
\par Ramsey checked the line telltales, switched on the stern eyes one by one.  "Laying to starboard about thirty degrees.  Towlines clear."
\par 
\par Sparrow tested the drive controls, switched on the motors.  A humming sense of expectancy came over the subtug.  Ramsey felt it tingle through his body, starting in his feet against the deck.
\par 
\par "Let's go get that oil," said Sparrow.  He threw in the drive switch, threw it off.  "Just to stir up the mud around us.  Drop four waist torpedoes, Johnny.  We'll need buoyancy."
\par 
\par "What about the tow?  It's not carrying enough pressure to blow at this depth."
\par 
\par "We're going to jerk it off the bottom.  Pay out line until we get a good run on."
\par 
\par Ramsey pushed down the flat black toggles which dropped the torpedoes from the waist belt.
\par 
\par The Ram hobbled upward.  Sparrow again threw power into the drive.  The subtug slanted upward, tow-line reeling out behind them.
\par 
\par "Snub it," said Sparrow.
\par 
\par Ramsey locked the magnetic brakes on the outside reel drums.  The tug came almost to a full stop, motors straining.  Slowly they struggled ahead.
\par 
\par "Line stretching," said Ramsey.  "That's slug's in solid."
\par 
\par Sparrow shook his head.  "How much more line?"
\par 
\par "Eight hundred feet more or less."
\par 
\par "Give us some more."
\par 
\par The Ram again angled upward.  Sparrow circled left, came back to the right in a snake track, barely moving.
\par 
\par "Operational depth," said Ramsey.  "Outside pressure 2994 pounds."
\par 
\par "Snub towlines and blow number-one tank," said Sparrow.
\par 
\par Again Ramsey stopped the outside reels.  His right hand went out to the red handle marked "high pressure air."  He set it over number one, flicked on the safety toggle, started bleeding air into the number-one tank.
\par 
\par "Give it everything," said Sparrow.
\par 
\par Ramsey turned the valve two revolutions.
\par 
\par Sparrow put full power into the drive.  The Ram's bow tipped up to almost ten degrees.  By niches, they climbed, twisting soggily.
\par 
\par "She's off," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par "How's the slug's compensator system?"
\par 
\par Ramsey looked to the tow board.  "Following the pressure curve."
\par 
\par "Blow the slug's bow and stern tanks," said Sparrow.  "She's not at --"
\par 
\par "Blow them anyway.  Water pressure will hold the air until we reach operational depth.  We're going to need all the help we can get and as soon as we can get it."
\par 
\par Ramsey's hands moved over the tow board carrying out his orders.
\par 
\par They inched upward.  Ramsey stared at the red dials of the slug's pressure system.  "Bow tank's beginning to bubble."
\par 
\par They could feel it in the deck:  a return to normal climb gradient, speed picking up.
\par 
\par "Bow tank just blew," said Ramsey.  "There goes the stern."  He wiped perspiration from his forehead.
\par 
\par "That was the thing Les should have considered," said Sparrow.  "Now we know we can get off.  As long as we have external weight which we can drop for the initial buoyancy."
\par 
\par "How do you know that Les didn't --"
\par 
\par "I know my shipmates," said Sparrow.  "Learn something from this, Johnny, and you'll make a good submariner.  Never head into anything with a sub unless you have already worked out a plan for coming out the other side."
\par 
\par Ramsey chose his words carefully.  "What's your plan for making the big come-out on the other side -- with the oil?"
\par 
\par "Not just one plan," said Sparrow.  "I have plans for every contingency I can think of.  And for some maybe I shouldn't have thought of."
\par 
\par "Like for instance?"
\par 
\par Sparrow turned and looked full at him.  "Like for instance my crew going psychotic, one by one."
\par 
\par Ramsey's eyes widened.  The words leaped out before he could stop them.  "And what about yourself?"
\par 
\par Sparrow's eyes glittered.  "That's one of the ones maybe I shouldn't have thought of," he said.  He swung back to the controls.
\par 
\par He's like a piece of machinery, thought Ramsey.  Great God in heaven, what went into making a man like that?
\par 
\par Bonnett entered carrying a hypodermic, its needle covered by a sterile pad.  "Time for your shot, Skipper."
\par 
\par "In my left arm?" asked Sparrow.
\par 
\par "Well --"
\par 
\par "Don't I get to keep any dignity?" asked Sparrow.
\par 
\par Ramsey grinned.
\par 
\par "I swear you guys take a perverse delight in this," growled Sparrow.
\par 
\par "It's really too much for your arm," said Bonnett.  He glanced up at the static gauge.  "Six thousand feet!  What're we doing up here in the shallows?"
\par 
\par Sparrow chuckled.  "Okay, take my mind off my troubles."  He backed away from the board.  "Take over here, Johnny.
\par 
\par Ramsey stepped into control position.  Behind him, he heard Sparrow grunt.  "Easy, Les!"
\par 
\par "Easy as I could, Skipper.  There.  Have Joe check you on his watch.  You seem to be coming along okay."
\par 
\par "I should be.  I've three nursemaids."
\par 
\par Sparrow moved up beside Ramsey.  "Hold us on course sixty-four degrees, forty-five minutes."
\par 
\par Ramsey turned the helm, looked up at the sonoran chart.  "That'll bring us around Nordkapp."  He did some mental figuring, glanced at the shaftlog counter.  "About twenty-six and a half hours."
\par 
\par Sparrow looked startled.
\par 
\par "He's good with figures," said Bonnett.
\par 
\par "He's also too interested in where we're, going to be and when," said Sparrow.
\par 
\par "That Security pap is for the birds," said Ramsey.  "I wish to remind you that we found a dead man aboard this vessel, that we've been sabotaged right and left, that --"  He broke off, staring at Ramsey.
\par 
\par It was Bonnett's turn to look startled.
\par 
\par And now I'm in over my head, thought Ramsey.  My plan had better be right or I won't . . . come out the other side.
\par 
\par Sparrow looked at the timelog.  "Time for Les to go on watch now."  He gestured for Bonnett to take the helm.  "Put us on auto-pilot.  Steady as she goes."
\par 
\par Ramsey went to the aft door, found Sparrow staring at him.  The captain turned deliberately away, moved closer to Bonnett.  "Stand by the search board as soon as we're on auto-pilot."
\par 
\par "Aye, Skipper."
\par 
\par Ramsey went out the door, swung it almost closed behind him, stood there with his ear to the crack.  Bonnett said, "How's Joe?"
\par 
\par "He's all right.  He'll stand his regular watch."
\par 
\par "What's with this Long John Ramsey?  Skipper, could he be a phony?"
\par 
\par "No doubt of it," said Sparrow.  "The only question in my mind is:  What kind of phony?"
\par 
\par "Could he be a --"
\par 
\par "He very definitely could be.  Someone loaded us with spy beams and trapped that Security officer."
\par 
\par "But Ramsey wasn't aboard then."
\par 
\par "That's what bothers me.  Unless there was something wrong with the Security man's timing.  That would explain it."
\par 
\par "I'll watch him, Skipper."
\par 
\par "You do that.  I'm also alerting Joe."
\par 
\par Ramsey tiptoed away from the door.  Well, I did it, he thought, I'd better be right.  He shuddered, turned at the end of the companionway, dropped down to his cabin level.  He paused in front of Garcia's cabin, looked at the blank metal of the door.  
Again the thought passed through his mind:  I'd better be right.
\par 
\par He went into his cabin, closing the door softly behind him, locking it.  Then he brought out the telemeter, unreeled the tapes.  There was response for Sparrow's time in the tunnel repairing the pile controls, but now Sparrow was under rigid control.  
The wave patterns on the tapes were like the path of a rubber ball bouncing between two walls.
\par 
\par I have to be able to crack that control at will, thought Ramsey.  He has to fail -- just once.  At the right time and at the right thing.
\par 
\par And another part of his mind said:  That's a helluva way to make someone well.
\par 
\par He fought down that thought.  It has to be.  It's accepted practice.  It works.  Most of the time.
\par 
\par Sparrow's advice came back to him:  "Never head into anything unless you have already worked out a plan for coming out the other side."
\par 
\par Ramsey sat down on his bunk, reset the telemeter, sealed it, slid it back beneath his desk.
\par 
\par What if my plan doesn't work?  What's my alternative for that contingency?
\par 
\par He lay back on his bunk, staring at the rivet pattern overhead.  Around him, the muted throbbing and humming of the subtug took on a fantasy life.  As though it knew where it was going and how to get there.
\par 
\par Ramsey fell into a troubled sleep, awoke for his next watch to find his body soaked in perspiration, a disturbing half memory of a dream -- no, a nightmare -- which he could not bring to consciousness.
