\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par The automatic timelog read twelve days, seven hours, and five minutes from departure.  Last half of Garcia's watch, first half of Bonnett's.  The red dot on the sonoran chart stood well into the shore
 off Nordkapp:  shallow water with the Ram creeping along the bottom in one hundred fathoms.
\par 
\par In the control room, a brightly lighted sweep of bulkhead, telltales flashing, heavy shadows on the undersides of levers and valve wheels.  Wavering admonitions of dial needles.  The two men bent over their work like laborers in a metal cave.
\par 
\par Bonnett looked up to the static pressure:  260 pounds to the square inch.  "What's the skipper thinking of, coming in close like this?"
\par 
\par "Don't ask so many questions."  Garcia made a minute adjustment in the bow planes, watched the depth repeater.  "We're twenty feet from bottom."
\par 
\par Sparrow ducked through the door from the aft companionway.  "Anything showing on the search board?"  His voice was husky with a sense of fatigue.  He coughed.
\par 
\par "Negative," said Bonnett.
\par 
\par "This is their water," said Sparrow.  "They've no shore stations along the north coast; only along the Norway reaches."
\par 
\par "This is still awful close," said Bonnett.  Again he looked to the depth gauge.  "And awful shallow."
\par 
\par "You don't think this is a safe place for us?" asked Sparrow.
\par 
\par "No."
\par 
\par "Good.  That means they don't either.  They know this is a deep tug.  They're out scouring the Norwegian basin.  The sill depth there is right on our known limit."
\par 
\par "So?"
\par 
