\par Dr. Oberhausen pursed his lips, tugged at his goatee.  "The old Napoleonic fancy-uniform therapy:  fanfare coming and going."  He nodded.  "Security will kick and scream that it will prevent secrecy of departures, but they've already made one concession."

\par 
\par "What?"
\par 
\par "They've announced officially that we're pirating oil from the EPs."
\par 
\par "That was a senseless secret anyway."
\par 
\par "They were reluctant."
\par 
\par "We'd be better off without Security," muttered Ramsey.  "We should be working to get rid of it.  Security stifles communication.  It's creating social schizophrenia."
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen gave a negative shake of his head.  "No, Johnny, we shouldn't get rid of Security.  That's an old fa
llacy.  Use Captain Sparrow's analogy:  In an insane society, a crazy man is normal.  Security has the kind of insanity that's normal for wartime.  Normal and needed."
\par 
\par "But after the war, Obe!  You know they're going to keep right on!"
\par 
\par "They'll try, Johnny.  But by that time we'll have Security under the control of BuPsych.  We'll be able to nullify them quite effectively."
\par 
\par Ramsey stared at him, then chuckled.  "So that's why you've been moving in on Belland."
\par 
\par "Not just Belland, Johnny."
\par 
\par "You scare me sometimes, Obe."
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen's goatee twitched.  "Good.  That means my pose of omnipotence is effective even with those who know better."  He smiled.
\par 
\par Ramsey grinned, stirred in his chair, "If that's all, Obe, I'd like to get away.  They wouldn't let Janet and the kids anywhere near me while I was in the hospital, and now that --"
\par 
\par "I waited, too, Johnny.  BuMed's little dictatorship halted even the great BuPsych.  There's an area of autonomy in radiation medicine that --"  He shook his head slowly.
\par 
\par "Well?" asked Ramsey.
\par 
\par "The impatience of youth," said Dr. Oberhausen.  "There are just a few more points to be cleared up.  Why do you believe we never saw the need for this fancy-uniform therapy?"
\par 
\par "Partly Security," said Ramsey.  "Bu
t it really wasn't obvious.  Wrong symptoms.  Napoleon was looking to build up enlistments and stop his gunners from going over the hill.  We've never had that trouble.  In fact, our submariners seemed eager to return to duty.  That's the paradox:  they f
o
und threat in both spheres -- ashore and at sea.  When they were ashore they seemed to forget about the menace of the sea because the subconscious masked it.  The boat spelled enveloping safety, a return to the womb.  But when the men came ashore, that wa
s birth:  exposure.  The sky's a hideous thing to men who want to hide from it."
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen cleared his throat.  His voice took on a crisp, business-like tone.  "Now, I'd like to go back to your notes for just a moment.  You say BuPsych should emphasize religious training.  Explain your reasoning."
\par 
\par Ramsey leaned forward and the telltale chair creaked.  "Because it's sanity, Obe.  That's the --"
\par 
\par "It smacks of a panacea, Johnny.  A nostrum."
\par 
\par "No, Obe.  A church provides a common bond for people
, a clear line of communication."  He shook his head.  "Unless BuPsych can uncover telepathy or absolute proof of the hereafter, it can't substitute for religion.  The sooner we face that, the sooner we'll be able to offer --"
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen slapped his hand on the desk top.  "Religion is not scientific!  It's faith!"  He said faith as he might have said dirty.
\par 
\par He's needling me, thought Ramsey.  He said, "Okay, Obe.  All I'm saying is this:  We don't have a substitute for religion.  But we're offering our so-called science as a substitute.  That's all I'm --"
\par 
\par "So-called?"
\par 
\par "How many distinct schools of psychology can you name?"
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen smiled thinly.  "At least as many as there are distinct religions."
\par 
\par "We're following the pattern even there," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par The BuPsych chief chuckled.  "Did I interrupt a chain of thought?"
\par 
\par Ramsey paused.  "Only that I've never met a psychoanalyst who didn't -- at least subconsciously -- offer his system as a substitute for religion.  Present compa
ny included.  We set ourselves up as little gods -- all-knowing, all-healing.  People resent that and rightly.  We have polite labels for our failures.  We agree among ourselves that anything bearing one of those labels is, of course, incurable."
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen's voice held a sense of remoteness.  "That's quite an indictment, Johnny.  Do I take it that you've been converted by our good Captain Sparrow?"
\par 
\par Ramsey leaned back, laughed.  "Hell, no!  I'm just going to stop posing as a messiah."
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen took a deep breath.  "That's encouraging."
\par 
\par "And I guess I'll go on poking around inside people's minds.  If that describes whatever it is we do."  He smiled.  "I'll keep on being a psychologist."
\par 
\par "What do you expect to find?"
\par 
\par Ramsey was silent a moment, then:  "A good scientist doesn't expect to find anything, Obe.  He reports what he sees."
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen clasped his hands.  "If you find God, please let me know."
\par 
\par "I'll do that."  Ramsey forced briskness into his voice.  "As long as we're clearing up loose ends, what about me?  When do I get out of this damned uniform and into my nice new department of BuPsych?"
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen pushed his chair back, resting his hands on the edge of the desk.  He tipped his head down, appeared to be st
aring at the bat-eye box.  "First, you'll have to play out your hero role.  The President's going to pin medals on all of you.  That's Belland's doing.  By the way, the admiral has given Mrs. Garcia a job in his department, his polite way of keeping her u
nder surveillance.  But it works out for the best of all concerned."
\par 
\par "In this best of all possible worlds," said Ramsey.  He sensed hesitancy in Dr. Oberhausen's manner.  "But when do I get out of the service?"
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen lifted his chin.  "I may not be able to get you out immediately, Johnny."
\par 
\par Ramsey felt pressure building up inside him.  "Why?"
\par 
\par "Well, you're a hero.  They'll want to exploit that."  The BuPsych chief cleared his throat.  "Some things are difficult even for BuPsych.  Look, I couldn't even get past BuMed and in to see you while --"
\par 
\par "You promised me a --"
\par 
\par "And I'll keep my promise, Johnny.  In time."  He leaned back.  "Meanwhile, there's a commodore on the board of classification and promotion.  He's a presidential errand boy and he needs an -- an aide-de-camp."
\par 
\par "Oh no!"  Ramsey stared at Dr. Oberhausen.
\par 
\par The little doctor shrugged.  "Well, Johnny, he found out that you're the clever Long John Ramsey who improvised a vampire gauge from a hypodermic and two glass tubes and saved the Dolphin during that training-mission breakdown.  He wants --"
\par 
\par Ramsey groaned.
\par 
\par "You'll be jumped to lieutenant," said Dr. Oberhausen.
\par 
\par "Thanks," said Ramsey bitterly.  He curled his lips, copied Dr. Oberhausen's voice:  "Sure, Johnny.  You'll have your own department."
\par 
\par "You're young," said Dr. Oberhausen.  "There's time."
\par 
\par "He'll have me polishing his shoes."
\par 
\par "Oh no.  He's quite impressed by your talents.  Says you're too good for BuPsych.  Bringing home that oil has done nothin
g to reduce his admiration."  Again the BuPsych chief cleared his throat.  "And while you're with the commodore there are some things about this department that I'd like you to --"
\par 
\par "So that's it!" barked Ramsey.  "Another of your damned spy jobs!  You want me to ferret out the dope on the commodore so you can move in on him.  I'll bet you set this job up yourself."
\par 
\par "I'm sure you see the necessity," said Dr. Oberhausen.  "That way lies sanity."
\par 
\par "I'm not so sure," said Ramsey.
\par 
\par "I like your Captain Sparrow's analogy about sanity and swimming," said Dr. Oberhausen.  "But I would add to it, the swimmer must be prepared at all times to grasp a paddle."
\par 
\par }{\f44\fs28\lang1033\langfe1049\langnp1033\insrsid6317202\charrsid6317202 Ramsey smiled even as he realized that Dr. Oberhausen was amusing him to ease the tension between them.  "Okay, Obe.  One more.  But I'm telling you now:  that's all."
\par 
\par "Fair enough, Johnny.  Now, if you'll just --"
\par 
\par A door slammed in the outer hall behind Ramsey.  He heard a flurry of sounds.  A woman's voice shouted:  "You can't stop me from going in there!"
\par 
\par Janet!
\par 
\par His pulse quickened.
\par 
\par The woman's voice mounted almost to a scream:  "I know he's in there with that damned Dr. Oberhausen!  And by Heaven I'm going in!"
\par 
\par The office door behind Ramsey burst open.  He turned.  It was a secretary.  "Please excuse me," she said.  "There's --"
\par 
\par "Let her come in," said Dr. Oberhausen.
\par 
\par Ramsey stood up, feeling suddenly giddy.  Janet came rushing through the door and into his arms.  A familiar perfume.  The contours of a familiar face pressing against his cheek, a familiar body against his own.
\par 
\par "Johnny!  Oh, Johnny!"
\par 
\par He heard Dr. Oberhausen get up, saw him walk past him toward the office door, fastening the bat-eye box to his shoulder as he went.
\par 
\par "Johnny, I missed you so."
\par 
\par "I missed you, too," he said.
\par 
\par "I never knew it would be so dangerous.  Why, they told me --"
\par 
\par "It wasn't bad, Janet.  Really."
\par 
\par "But you were so long in the hospital!"
\par 
\par Dr. Oberhausen paused at the door, a figure in new perspective, grown suddenly smaller, giving off a sense of loneliness.  Ramsey wanted to call out something but didn't know what.  He said, "Obe."
\par 
\par The BuPsych chief turned.
\par 
\par "We'll see you soon," said Ramsey.
